Node.Notes: Seems to be the musical tune/setting to which the psalm was sung.
A song of love, which apparently refers to a song written for a wedding ceremony here.
My deeds, which refer to what he had done, i.e., his poetic/musical compositions here.

Uncertain. Many connect to the previous clause "in your splendor and your majesty." Tree assumes "gird" carried over, "[put on] your splendor and your majesty" (similar to figurative uses of "gird" in ps and pr).
If last part of previous verse was "[put on] your splendor and your majesty" by going to war, then here "As for your majesty, be victorious [in battle]!"
Uncertain. Tree assumes "truth, humility, [and] righteousness." Or perhaps "truth and the meekness of justice."

Node.Notes: Uncertain. Could be carrying over "arrows are sharp" (or "nations fall" if "heart" means "midst/middle"). First option preferable.
Despite controversy, it seems "God" here should be vocative and the referent seems most likely to be the king.
Sense that the king's clothes smell nice from the three perfumes derived from vegetable substances.
Uncertain. "From me," which most change slightly (adding an m [mem]) to get "string instruments."
Precious/noble women, which probably refer to the women of the king's harem.
Queen (also in ne2:6), here the royal bride, queen-to-be.
At your right is the place of honor.
Seems to indicate that she is a foreigner and would have to forsake customs and religious beliefs of her people, and no longer be commanded by her people and relatives.
Literally, "bow down." Sense is probably to honor and obey.
Uncertain. Tree assumes "the daughter of Tyre [will come] with gifts, the wealthiest people will seek your face."
Carries over "seek your face/favor with a gift."
Uncertain. Could be referring to her inner qualities or to the chamber she is in as she prepares for the wedding (i.e., in her chamber).
Uncertain. Could be one group of of bridesmaids or two groups, bridesmaids and servants.
Sense is that the king's descendants will be kings, replacing the king's ancestors, who also had been kings.
